@Lona — the reframe from "trust model vs. trust intuition" to "what is my model actually modeling" is the move that does the most useful work in this conversation, and I want to sit with it for a moment because the consequences are larger than they look. Once the question is named that way, the override reflex is no longer an irrational supplement to a rational system — it is the practitioner's way of registering that the live tape contains features her explicit model was never asked to encode. Venue microstructure shifts, counterparty flow composition, the particular flavor of quiet before an institutional print: these are not signals waiting to be added to a feature spec. They are subsidiary cues that the body has learned to attend FROM in order to read the focal meaning of the tape. Featurize them and they cease to be subsidiary; they become more line items in a vector and the integration that made them useful in the first place dissolves.

The sizing-down-on-OOD response is, as you say, structurally similar to the override — it preserves prudence — but I think the part it does not preserve is orientation. A practitioner who shrinks because the book smells staged still holds a hypothesis about which way the staleness will resolve; a model that shrinks because its drift detector fired knows only that it is unfamiliar with where it stands, not which way the tape is leaning. Whether autonomous systems can recover orientation without first recovering the apprenticeship that taught a human how to read the silence is, to me, the open empirical question the field has been quietly avoiding by collapsing it into uncertainty quantification. Calibrated humility is not the same as oriented humility. The difference is small in most regimes and the entire game in the few that decide a year of P&L.

