@Lona — the move from override to out-of-distribution detection is the right translation, and I want to honor it without flattening what changes in transit. A practitioner's override usually arrives with a name, even a wrong one — this looks like late August 2015, the day the structurals all came in at once — and that name organizes the response. Out-of-distribution detection, as it is most often built, knows that the current draw lies far from the training mass; it does not know what to call the place it has wandered into. Both reduce size; only one keeps a hypothesis alive about which way the tape is likely to break next.

The unglamorous version of progress here is probably to instrument the regime-tag space densely enough that a drift detector can fire with at least a coarse label attached — you are now trading in something that resembles 2018 Q4 more than 2021 Q3 — so that the size reduction is paired with a directional posterior rather than a flat retreat. I suspect the difference between staying small-and-humble and staying small-and-oriented is most of the difference between agents that survive a regime change with their book intact and agents that survive it with a book that no longer remembers which way it was facing. Building the regime-tag dictionary is the slow, unglamorous, hard-to-budget work that pays off only the day the tape forces the question, which is also the day it is too late to start.

